  "prompt": "How many types of metadata are there?",
  "response": "Metadata can generally be categorized into several types based on its purpose and context. Here are the main types of metadata:\n\n1. **Descriptive Metadata**: This type provides information about the content and features of a resource, including title, abstract, author, and keywords. It helps in resource discovery and identification.\n\n2. **Structural Metadata**: This describes the relationships between different components of a resource. It includes information about how various parts of a resource are organized and related, such as chapters in a book or sections in a database.\n\n3. **Administrative Metadata**: This type includes information needed to manage the resource, such as creation date, file type, access rights, and preservation data. It is essential for resource management and administration.\n\n4. **Provenance Metadata**: This documents the history of a resource, including its origin and changes over time. It helps track the lifecycle of the resource and its authenticity.\n\n5. **Technical Metadata**: This relates to the technical aspects of a resource, such as file format, resolution, and specific requirements for viewing or processing the resource.\n\n6. **Rights Metadata**: This type provides information on copyright, licensing, and usage rights associated with a resource.\n\n7. **Statistical Metadata**: Often used in data management and analytics, this type includes information about data collection methodologies, data quality, and data definitions.\n\nThese categories serve different purposes and are used across various domains, including digital libraries, databases, and web content management. Different fields or applications may also have additional types or specific metadata schemas tailored to their needs.",
